How the World is Stopping Sexual Harassment in Film

Nichole Yao, Yuqing Geng, Rowan Wheeler

Dec 14th, 2017

Get the data on GitHub

Director Patty Jenkins and lead actor Gal Gadot on the set of $800m blockbuster Wonder Woman. Photograph: Clay Enos.

Almost daily, another prominent man in Hollywood is accused of sexual harassment. As the voices of powerful female actors, directors, producers, and other film industry figures have spoken out against sexual harassment, The #MeToo movement 1 in the United States has had a profound impact. It has held many powerful men accountable for their inappropriate conduct. It has even been named the 2017 Times Magazine Person of the Year. However, the impact of this movement has spread beyond the United States. As it struggles to change its toxic environment, Hollywood must look globally to determine what other actions it can take to prevent harassment in the future.

As the amount of women working in the global film industry grows, womens voices increase in power, both onscreen and off 2. To create more opportunities for women in film, Hollywood must look internationally to learn from actions taken by other countries. To gain insight into the history of women in Hollywood, we examined how the percentage of women in positions of power in Hollywood has changed over time and how that percentage compares to international percentages of female filmmakers. We wanted to know if the United States has higher levels of female producers and directors than other countries and how other countries responded to the #MeToo movement.

Women in Hollywood

A 2015 report from researchers at Kent State University and the University of Texas at Tyler found that the prevalence of male norms in the male-dominated environment may result in a more hostile workplace for women who are perceived by men as violators of the gender norms. The overwhelming power held by male producers and directors within Hollywood creates a breeding ground for sexual harassment.

Harassment also occurs when people are seen as disposable. Companies pay millions of dollars in settlements to protect their star performers, as Fox did with Bill OReilly. In Hollywood, where knowing the right people can help you gain or lose a job and one word from a powerful industry figure can ruin your career, sexual harassment is all too easy to perpetrate. Changing such a widespread problem wont be easy. As long as male-driven movies are created by and for men, Hollywood will still value mens voices more, and so continue to prevent female victims from speaking out without fear of ostracism. The best way to change this trend is to prioritize women in positions of power, and not just in front of the camera: as directors and producers as well.

install.packages("stringi")
library(stringi)
library(mdsr)
library(RMySQL)
library(dplyr)
library(plyr)
db <- dbConnect_scidb(dbname = "imdb")
big_data<- db%>% 
dbGetQuery("SELECT n.name, n.id AS person_id, n.gender, ci.movie_id, t.production_year,ci.role_id, mi.info AS country
FROM imdb.person_info pi
JOIN name n ON pi.person_id = n.id
JOIN cast_info ci ON ci.person_id = n.id
JOIN movie_info mi ON ci.movie_id = mi.movie_id
JOIN title t ON t.id = mi.movie_id
WHERE (ci.role_id = 3
OR ci.role_id = 8)
AND t.kind_id = 1
AND mi.info_type_id = 8
AND mi.info IN('China','USA','Australia','India','Canada')
AND t.production_year <2017
AND t.production_year >1939;")
big_data1<- distinct(big_data)
big_data2 <- na.omit(big_data1)
save(big_data2,file = "big_data.rda")
library(mdsr)
library(RMySQL)
library(dplyr)
library(plyr)
load("big_data.rda")

# Producer
big_data3<- big_data2 %>%
  filter(role_id ==3, country == "USA" )%>%
  mutate(decade = 10 * floor(production_year / 10))%>%
  select(decade,gender,country) %>%
  group_by(decade, gender) %>% 
  dplyr::summarize(N = n(), male = sum(ifelse(gender =="m",1,0)),
female = sum(ifelse(gender =="f",1,0)))
big_data4<- big_data3 %>%
  group_by(decade) %>%
  dplyr::summarize(N=n(),m = sum(male), f = sum(female))

d_percentage<- big_data4 %>%
  mutate(total = m+f,
  male_percentage = m/total, 
  female_percentage = f/total) %>%
  select(male_percentage, female_percentage, decade, total) %>% 
  tidyr::gather(key = "gender", value = "percentage", -decade, -total)

d_percentage <- ddply(d_percentage, .(decade),
                transform, pos = cumsum(percentage) - (0.5 * percentage))
p3 <- ggplot() + geom_bar(aes(y = round(percentage,digits =2), x = decade, fill = gender), data = d_percentage, stat="identity") + 
geom_text(data=d_percentage, aes(x = decade, y = pos, label = paste0(round(percentage, digits= 2)*100,"%")), size=4) + 
   labs(x = "Decades", y = "Percentage", title="Percentage of US Female Producers in the Past Decades")+ 
 scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0,1), breaks = c(0,0.25,0.50,0.75,1), labels = scales::percent)+
theme(text=element_text(family="Times New Roman", face="bold", size=12), legend.position="bottom", legend.direction="horizontal",
                  legend.title = element_blank()) + 
                  scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(1880,2010,10))
p3

We took data from the International Movie Database, also known as IMDb. IMDb contains information about millions of pieces of media, including television, online content, and movies. We found the listed gender of the directors and producers of movies made in the United States, then grouped them by decade. Clearly, while the percentage has increased over time, women producers and directors are still a minority in their fields. With a relatively stable increase of a roughly 5% increase per decade, based on the historic rate it will take another five decades for women in leadership roles in Hollywood to reflect real life gender ratios. While we looked at a large set of movies, including lower budget films, these percentages would be even lower for big budget movies and more popular movies shown in wide release. According to the Media, Diversity, & Social Change Initiative out of USC Annenberg, as budgets increase, opportunities for female filmmakers decrease. Their data shows that from 2007-2016, women directed only 4% of top-grossing films in Hollywood. This Initiative and other watchgroups focus on popular movies. They argue that these movies matter more because they get more attention and funding, and so affect the public view of Hollywood that affects sexual harassment claims. Since our data encompasses genres like short films and independent films, it presents a higher proportion of female directors and producers than the one presented by their data. However, with the film industry expanding and films being produced on even more platforms and budgets, we felt it was important to acknowledge the opportunities female creators on all budgets have created for themselves. As it gets easier to release original content, more independent creators of all genders, races, and professional levels have been able to gain audiences, voices, and therefore enough clout in the film industry to speak up about sexual harassment.

#MeToo, a Global Movement

We wanted to see if this increase in female filmmakers was only in the United States, or if a similar trend could be observed worldwide. Had other countries also been incorporated into the #MeToo movement, and what efforts had they made to increase representation of women creators? We compared five of the largest global film industries: the United States, India, Canada, Australia, and China.

# count bar graph if needed
big_data8<- big_data2 %>%
  mutate(decade = 10 * floor(production_year / 10))%>%
  select(decade,gender,country) %>%
  group_by(decade, gender,country) %>% 
  dplyr::summarize(N = n(), male = sum(ifelse(gender =="m",1,0)),
female = sum(ifelse(gender =="f",1,0)))
big_data9<- big_data8 %>%
  group_by(decade,country) %>%
  dplyr::summarize(m = sum(male), 
                   f = sum(female),
                   total = m+f,
                   female_percentage = f/total)
ggplot(big_data9,aes(x=decade, y=female_percentage))+
  geom_smooth(se=FALSE, aes(color = country))+
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0,1),labels = scales::percent, breaks = c(0,0.25,0.5,0.75,1))+
  labs(x = "Decades", y = "Percentage", title="Percentage of Female Creators Among Five Countries in the Past Decades")+
theme(text=element_text(family="Times New Roman", face="bold", size=12))

IMDb meticulously records Western films, but it does not have as detailed information on international films in languages besides English. Many movies released in India and China are not registered on IMDb, especially the lower-budget movies that women are more likely to direct or produce, so our data may be skewed. Even so, it is clear that the amount of female filmmakers has been increasing worldwide.

Krew Boylan, Rose Byrne, Jessica Carrera, Shannon Murphy and Gracie Otto, the founders of Dollhouse Pictures. Dollhouse Pictures is an Australian independent production company which prioritises female-driven storytelling.

Despite the global growth of women in film, the movement to end sexual assault is occurring almost exclusively in countries like Australia and Canada, who share relatively similar cultures and percentages of female filmmakers as the United States. In 2015, a group of female Directors Guild members, led by Gillian Armstrong 3, pressured the Australian governments public screen production fund to address the lack of female directors within Australian film. Australia established several initiatives, including a three ticks policy, which ensured that 50% of all film projects the government backed by 2019 would have women in three of four creatives roles: producer, director, writer, or lead actor. This week, Australia announced that it was creating a sexual harassment code of practice that all film and TV companies must follow to be given government funding. A similar effort took place from 1974-1996 in Canada, where the Canadian government funded an studio which would exclusively make films by women filmmakers for and about women. It was a critical success, creating Oscar winning films about boundary-pushing social issues, but eventually ended due to lack of government funding. Australia and Canada used control of government funds to support female filmmakers, but Hollywood is almost exclusively driven by private companies. In order to take steps like Australias, Hollywood must promote stricter standards and financial incentives to increase its amount of female directors and producers. By doing so, women will be given the space they need to tell their stories, whether fictional or all too real.

  1. Me Too is a hashtag used on social media against sexual assault and harassment, in the wake of sexual misconduct allegations against film producer and executive Harvey Weinstein (Wikipedia)
